[by 
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F7215FE68FA56FE27" author="Kirby, W. F." box="[1294,1435,386,410]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="249 - 348" refId="ref43156" refString="Kirby, W. F. 1889. A revision of the subfamily Libellulinae, with descriptions of new genera and species. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London 12: 249 - 348." type="journal article" year="1889">Kirby 1889</bibRefCitation>
, subsequent designation].
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="328BFC984106512F77DBFE0BFA4AFC87" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7A2EAF134106512F77DBFE0BFA4AFC87" blockId="10.[192,1441,481,826]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F77DBFE0BFE9DFE44" bold="true" box="[192,336,481,505]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Hind femur thickened with numerous and distally directed short spines on its basal half, followed by 3–5 long robust spines on its distal half. In many specimens some spines of intermediate size may be observed (
<figureCitation id="E2AAB3964106512F76CDFDC8FDE3FD84" box="[470,558,545,570]" captionStart="Figures 10–17" captionStartId="57.[192,286,1788,1810]" captionTargetBox="[205,1428,192,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-93@57.[205,1428,192,1774]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figures 10–17. Discrete characters of vulvar lamina, abdominal appendages, thorax, and femur.Numbers represent the following species: 10) E. peruviana female; 11) E. plebeja female; 12) E. simplicicollis male; 13) E. mithroides male; 14) E. vesiculosa male; 15) E. peruviana female; 16) E. vesiculosa female, 17) E. attala male. Abbreviations indicate the following characters, S 8 -S 9: Abdominal segments 8-9; LV: Vulvar lamina; Pb: Posterior border; Vt: Teeth ventral; Ai: Inferior appendage; As: Antehumeral stripe." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353165/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Thorax either brown, reddish-brown, black, green or blue. Abdominal dorsum either brown, reddish-brown, red, black, green and black or blue. Prothorax with a small, decumbent posterior lobe constricted at base and upright. Abdomen: S1-3 swollen and S4-10 narrow, the genus species have either slender and elongate or shaped abdomen. HW entirely hyaline or with a dark basal spot, last antenodal incomplete, Mspl and Rspl distinct, radial planates with one or two rows of cells throughout; median planate with one row of cells. Other characters useful in recognizing 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F77DBFD08FEF3FD47" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[192,318,738,762]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Erythemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F77DBFD08FEF3FD47" box="[192,318,738,762]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Erythemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
proposed by Garrison et al. (2006) are: MP in HW arising at or near anal angle of triangle or distinctly separated from anal angle of triangle; anterior lamina complete; posterior hamule bifid with inner branch smaller than outer branch; vulvar lamina scoop shaped and projecting ventrally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="328BFC984106512F77DBFC84FD78FBDB" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7A2EAF134106512F77DBFC84FD78FBDB" blockId="10.[192,1440,878,1126]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F77DBFC84FEF1FC3B" bold="true" box="[192,316,878,902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F7651FC85FE3DFC3B" author="Hagen, H. A." box="[330,496,878,903]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 347" refId="ref42705" refString="Hagen, H. A. 1861. Synopsis of the Neuroptera of North America, with a list of the South American species. Smithsonian miscellaneous Collections, 4: 1 - 347." type="journal article" year="1861">Hagen (1861)</bibRefCitation>
established three genera for new and previously described species of dragonflies. The first, 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F7667FC64FE36FC1B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[380,507,910,934]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Lepthemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F7667FC64FE36FC1B" box="[380,507,910,934]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Lepthemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(p. 160), the second, 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F7419FC64FC4DFC1B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[770,896,910,934]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Erythemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F7419FC64FC4DFC1B" box="[770,896,910,934]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Erythemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(p. 168) and the third, 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F73B8FC64FAFEFC1B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[1187,1331,910,934]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Mesothemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F73B8FC64FAFEFC1B" box="[1187,1331,910,934]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Mesothemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(p. 170). 
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F77DBFC44FE96FC7B" author="Gloyd, L. K." box="[192,347,942,966]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="103 - 104" refId="ref42521" refString="Gloyd, L. K. 1980. The status of the generic names Erythemis, Lepthemis and Mesothemis (Anisoptera: Libellulidae). Notulae Odonatologicae 1: 103 - 104." type="journal article" year="1980">Gloyd (1980)</bibRefCitation>
discussed the dual use of the generic names 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F7461FC44FC34FC7B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[890,1017,942,966]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Lepthemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F7461FC44FC34FC7B" box="[890,1017,942,966]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Lepthemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(monotypic genus) and 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F7201FC44FA55FC7B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[1306,1432,942,966]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Erythemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F7201FC44FA55FC7B" box="[1306,1432,942,966]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Erythemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and discussed that page priority was not sufficient reason to choose 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F7312FC24FB45FC5B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[1033,1160,974,998]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Lepthemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F7312FC24FB45FC5B" box="[1033,1160,974,998]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Lepthemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
over 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F73D7FC24FA87FC5B" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[1228,1354,974,998]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Erythemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F73D7FC24FA87FC5B" box="[1228,1354,974,998]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Erythemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, although the nominal genus 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F753DFC04FC80FBBB" authority="Hagen, 1861" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[550,845,1006,1031]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Lepthemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F753DFC04FD68FBBB" box="[550,677,1006,1030]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Lepthemis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F75B5FC05FC80FBBB" author="Hagen, H. A." box="[686,845,1006,1031]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 347" refId="ref42705" refString="Hagen, H. A. 1861. Synopsis of the Neuroptera of North America, with a list of the South American species. Smithsonian miscellaneous Collections, 4: 1 - 347." type="journal article" year="1861">Hagen, 1861</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, can be selected to take precedence by the First Reviser action (Article 24.2, International Code of Zoological Nomenclature 1999), Pinto et al. (2012) proposed to conserve the widespread usage of the generic name 
<taxonomicName id="BD91D4904106512F74DEFBC4FB2BFBFB" authority="Hagen, 1861" authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1861" box="[965,1254,1070,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Erythemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48E573014106512F74DEFBC4FB8EFBFB" box="[965,1091,1070,1094]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Erythemis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F7351FBC5FB2BFBFB" author="Hagen, H. A." box="[1098,1254,1070,1095]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 347" refId="ref42705" refString="Hagen, H. A. 1861. Synopsis of the Neuroptera of North America, with a list of the South American species. Smithsonian miscellaneous Collections, 4: 1 - 347." type="journal article" year="1861">Hagen, 1861</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, under Articles 23.9.3 and 81.1 of the Code (
<bibRefCitation id="1E00D2E24106512F7507FBA4FD65FBDB" author="ICZN &amp; International Code of Zoological Nomenclature" box="[540,680,1102,1126]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" refId="ref42867" refString="ICZN [International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]. 1999. Fourth edition. The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London, xxix + 306 pp. Available at http: // www. nhm. ac. uk / hosted-sites / iczn / code / (Accessed on August 07, 2012)." type="book" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
